oakcurric:unit-157
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'Small Island'"@en ;
  curric:slug "small-island" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils explore the playtext adaptation of Andrea Levy's novel 'Small
  Island'. They first explore the transition from novel to stage, before reading the
  playtext in full and exploring key scenes in detail. They then plan and write an essay on
  the theme of 'hope' in the text."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' understanding of drama and stagecraft
  from 'The Tempest', developing their understanding of identity and belonging from the
  characters Ariel and Caliban. The unit also builds on pupils' understanding of belonging and
  identity from the 'Single Poet Study: Maya Angelou' unit. Pupils are prepared for the four
  'Leave Taking' units in Years 10 and 11 by being given a grounding in modern theatre
  stagecraft and how Black female British writers have explored modern British identity and
  belonging, which is further developed in 'Leave Taking'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-157-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-157-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-157-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-157-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-157-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-157-6 ;
  curric:id "157"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.009391Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-modern-literature-strand-1-identity-belonging-and-community .

oakcurric:unit-145
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Taking a stand"@en ;
  curric:slug "taking-a-stand" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the different ways that writers have expressed
  their points of view across history. They look at some key techniques that writers use,
  such as motif and triad, before reading a speech, article, poem and song. They finally
  write and deliver their own presentation."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This is the first time in the curriculum that pupils have developed
  non-fiction writing and written presentations for performance. In this unit, pupils gain a
  strong foundation in their understanding of non-fiction conventions, and start to learn how
  to craft and deliver spoken language presentations. This unit prepares pupils for the
  'Victorian childhood' unit, where they will practise giving presentations in a parliamentary
  debate, as well as answering questions about their topic.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-145-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-145-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-145-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-145-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-145-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-145-6 ;
  curric:id "145"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.222508Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-non-fiction-reading-and-writing ,
    oakcurric:thread-developing-spoken-language .

oakcurric:unit-72
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Step into the unknown: fiction reading and creative writing"@en ;
  curric:slug "step-into-the-unknown-fiction-reading-and-creative-writing" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils develop their fiction reading and creative writing by reading
  extracts from famous fiction and then emulating key techniques in their own writing. They
  start by securing and extending their knowledge of key sentence grammar, before reading
  and emulating the extracts."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This units uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of fiction and descriptive
  writing from their primary school curriculum. This unit introduces them to many of the key
  components of secondary English study, and gives them a strong grounding in both analytical
  reading and creative writing. This sets them up for the rest of the secondary English
  curriculum. This unit particularly prepares pupils for the 'Dystopian settings' unit where
  they will build on their understanding of sentence structure and variation from this unit and
  start to utilise it to create atmospheric settings.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-72-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-72-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-72-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-72-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-72-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-72-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-72-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-72-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-72-9 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-72-10 ;
  curric:id "72"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.227319Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-fiction-writing .

oakcurric:unit-147
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "A monster within: reading and writing Gothic fiction"@en ;
  curric:slug "a-monster-within-reading-gothic-fiction" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils explore the Gothic. They start by learning what the Gothic
  is, before reading extracts from 'Frankenstein' and 'Jane Eyre', practising descriptive
  writing and reading 'The Tell-Tale Heart'. They finally learn how to write opinion
  articles and then write their own."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils first introduction to gothic ideas and
  themes in 'The Twisted Tree'. Pupils now read extracts from some of the most famous gothic
  texts in history, and analyse more deeply how they have been constructed. They also extend
  their understanding of fiction and non-fiction writing by deepening their understanding of
  gothic conventions. This unit prepares pupils for the 'gothic poetry' unit where they will
  look in more detail at how the Gothic is expressed in different formats.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-147-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-147-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-147-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-147-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-147-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-147-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-147-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-147-8 ;
  curric:id "147"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.628664Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-exploring-the-gothic ,
    oakcurric:thread-developing-fiction-writing ,
    oakcurric:thread-nineteenth-century-literature .

oakcurric:unit-163
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Poetry about place and home"@en ;
  curric:slug "poetry-about-place-and-home" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read and respond to poems that explore the links between
  place and identity. They start by exploring a selection of poems including Grace Nichol's
  'Island Man' and Lemn Sissay's 'Anthem of the North'. They then write and perform their
  own poems about place and home."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils explored a wide range of poetry in our primary curriculum, with a
  focus on how poets, including Joseph Coelho and Matt Goodfellow, responded to place in their
  poems. Pupils now read more complex secondary poets, and start to use analytical skills to
  explore the methods writers use to respond to place. They also start to emulate those more
  complex techniques so that their poetry writing and appreciation becomes more accomplished.
  Later in the curriculum, pupils look at Maya Angelou's poetry in depth to explore how context
  shapes a writer's voice, and then find their own poetic voice.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-163-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-163-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-163-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-163-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-163-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-163-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-163-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-163-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-163-9 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-163-10 ;
  curric:id "163"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.637143Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-modern-literature-strand-1-identity-belonging-and-community ,
    oakcurric:thread-appreciation-of-poetry .

oakcurric:unit-164
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Sherlock Holmes: short stories"@en ;
  curric:slug "sherlock-holmes-short-stories" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read and explore two famous Sherlock Holmes stories. They
  start by reading and analysing 'The Speckled Band' before using it as inspiration to write
  a newspaper article. They then read and analyse 'The Boscombe Valley Murder' before
  writing a comparison of the two stories."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' reading and initial exploration of
  Sherlock Holmes in the primary curriculum. In primary, pupils explored retellings of Sherlock
  stories, but they now read Arthur Conan Doyle's original language in full and complete more
  analysis of his stories. They also start to learn about the Victorian context in which he was
  writing, which prepares them for later study of Victorian literature. This unit particulary
  prepares pupils for the unit 'A Monster Within', where they will read increasingly
  challenging nineteenth century literature and learn about the Gothic.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-164-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-164-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-164-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-164-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-164-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-164-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-164-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-164-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-164-9 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-164-10 ;
  curric:id "164"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.640646Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-3 .

oakcurric:unit-159
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Myths, legends and stories that inspire"@en ;
  curric:slug "myths-and-legends-re-told-poetry-and-short-stories" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read and explore a range of text types in connection to
  classical myths and legends. They first look at poetry before doing some descriptive
  writing inspired by poetry and paintings. They then explore Chaucer and modern retellings
  of myths to inspire their narrative writing."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' understanding of fiction and creative
  writing from the Year 7 unit 'Step into the unknown'. In this unit, they build on their
  understanding of how writers create vivid descriptions by looking at how they utilise
  powerful imagery and symbolism to make their writing more impactful. This unit prepares
  pupils for a number of units, including their first reading of 'Animal Farm' in Key Stage 4.
  In 'Animal Farm', pupils will learn more about how symbolism and allegory can be used to
  carry powerful messages.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-159-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-159-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-159-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-159-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-159-5 ;
  curric:id "159"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.719105Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-fiction-writing .

oakcurric:unit-3722
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Participating in effective debates"@en ;
  curric:slug "participating-in-effective-debates" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about debate and practise having debates. They first
  learn what a debate is, before presenting arguments for a debate and then learning how you
  create rebuttals in debates. Pupils then finish the unit by having a debate."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on the primary English units where pupils started to have
  simple structured debates. It also builds on the secondary English unit, 'the fundamentals of
  effective discussion', where pupils learnt about how to form opinions and listen carefully to
  others. In this unit, pupils learn how they can use their active listening skills to
  understand and counter other people's arguements. This unit builds towards the unit 'creating
  and performing slam poetry', where pupils will continue to build their confidence in
  articulating themselves in public speaking.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3722-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3722-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3722-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3722-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3722-5 ;
  curric:id "3722"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.789358Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-3 .

oakcurric:unit-156
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Malevolent characters: fiction writing"@en ;
  curric:slug "malevolent-characters-descriptive-and-narrative-writing" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils create and write malevolent characters. They first look at
  the conventions of malevolent characters, before learning about the techniques they can
  use to present their malevolent characters. They finally plan and write their fiction with
  a malevolent character in it."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' understanding of narrative and
  descriptive writing from 'Myths, legends and stories that inspire'. Pupils now start to look
  beyond just narrative and description, and learn the importance of creating characters with
  distinct identities. In the process, they further develop their skills as a writer by
  utilising the power of dialogue and juxtaposition. This unit prepares pupils for the unit
  'Fiction: read around the world' where they start emulating classic texts by practising how
  to write key specific parts of a narrative or description.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-156-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-156-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-156-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-156-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-156-5 ;
  curric:id "156"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.947245Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-exploring-the-gothic ,
    oakcurric:thread-developing-fiction-writing .

oakcurric:unit-148
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Gothic poetry"@en ;
  curric:slug "gothic-poetry" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read and explore two nineteenth-century gothic poems by Edgar
  Allen Poe. They first read and analyse 'The Raven' and 'The Haunted Palace' in isolation,
  before comparing them to each other and developing a personal response. Finally, they
  practise performing one of the poems."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' new understanding of the Gothic from
  'A Monster Within'. Having learnt about gothic fiction in 'A Monster Within', pupils now see
  how gothic themes can be expressed in poetry. This prepares pupils for the 'Malevolent
  characters' unit, where they will use their understanding of gothic fiction to write gothic
  stories.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-148-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-148-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-148-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-148-4 ;
  curric:id "148"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.309669Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-exploring-the-gothic ,
    oakcurric:thread-appreciation-of-poetry .

oakcurric:unit-162
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'The Tempest'"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-tempest" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the plot and characters of Shakespeare's 'The
  Tempest', and read sections of the play. They explore how Prospero treats Ariel, Caliban
  and Miranda, and write monlogues from their perspectives. Finally, they write and perform
  their own monologues inspired by the play."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have encountered some aspects of Shakespeare's plays
  at primary school. This unit is a bridge between primary and secondary study of Shakespeare.
  Rather than read the whole play, pupils explore key sections to deepen their understanding.
  Similarly, pupils complete creative and spoken responses to the play rather than academic
  critical essays. This helps to ease their transition between primary and secondary studies of
  Shakespeare. This unit also starts pupils' exploration of outsiders within Shakespeare's
  play, which is developed across all of our Shakespeare units.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-162-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-162-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-162-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-162-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-162-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-162-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-162-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-162-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-162-9 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-162-10 ;
  curric:id "162"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.633884Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-shakespeare-and-the-outsider .

oakcurric:unit-3807
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Simon Armitage: writing your world"@en ;
  curric:slug "simon-armitage-writing-your-world" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn more about how to read and write poetry by listening to
  words of wisdom from the Poet Laureate, Simon Armitage. They read a range of his poems
  about his life and the wider world, and start to write increasingly poetically in response
  to them."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils understanding of poetry from the unit
  'Singe poet study: Maya Angelou'. In that unit, pupils started to think more deeply about how
  and why poets write about their worlds. In this unit, pupils gain a richer understanding of
  poetry by hearing directly from one of the most prominent poets in the world, Simon Armitage.
  They start to recognise where poems come from, and how they have been crafted for effect.
  This prepares pupils for the first GCSE Poetry Anthology units, where pupils start to develop
  personal interpretations about a wider range of poetry.""" ;
  curric:id "3807"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.714559Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-appreciation-of-poetry .

oakcurric:unit-146
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Victorian childhood: non-fiction reading and writing"@en ;
  curric:slug "victorian-childhood-non-fiction-reading-and-writing" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read a mixture of contemporary and nineteenth-century
  non-fiction texts that explore a common theme of childhood. They first read and compare
  the texts, before then writing and delivering a speech as part of a debate on Victorian
  working class children."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' understanding of non-fiction writing
  and presentation delivery from 'Taking a stand'. In this unit, they learn to create more
  sophisticated presentations by first learning more about a topic through wide reading. They
  also learn to develop a speech as part of a debate, which develops the dynamism of their
  spoken language. This unit preapres pupils for 'Women's rights across the ages', where they
  will develop and refine their spoken language capabities by learning more about tone and
  language choices.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-146-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-146-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-146-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-146-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-146-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-146-6 ;
  curric:id "146"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.089686Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-non-fiction-reading-and-writing ,
    oakcurric:thread-developing-spoken-language ,
    oakcurric:thread-nineteenth-century-literature .

